name: trifluoroacetic anhydride
Reason: The basic unit for comparison here is acetic acid, which has a melting point of 16.6 °C. Trifluoroacetic anhydride is derived from trifluoroacetic acid, where the acidic proton is replaced with a trifluoromethyl group connected via an oxygen atom. Trifluoromethyl groups significantly increase the electronegativity and lower the melting point due to their electron-withdrawing nature, which weakens intermolecular hydrogen bonding compared to acetic acid. Each trifluoromethyl group might contribute roughly -30 °C. The anhydride linkage further lowers the melting point compared to the single acid unit, by an estimated -10 °C. Substituting two trifluoromethyl groups and one anhydride linkage results in a melting point that is lower than that of acetic acid: 16.6 - (2*30) - 10.
